ohhhh the dating scene! lort have mercy on me,as i step back into a this mad mad world again! 
keep me safe and find me a chef who loves you &  yoga as much as i do hahahaha! 
i can’t believe how many men still ask this question! 
well i have a list of my own! like can you even see your toes? (jk-as it’s pretty obvious!) what medications are you on? 
any past injuries, ( knees-hips or shoulders) 
are your parents still alive & do you live with them 
how many ex wife’s/girlfriends are still active in your life? (believe it or not a lot!) children/grandchildren? 
military? 
do you still drive a car? 
bahahhhaa you may giggle but honestly as you get older lol there are other priorities than “do you own a house!” keep me in your prayers and thoughts as the jungle opens up! of course i would never ask them all those questions lol but that doesn’t mean i don’t think of them lol! 
anyway let’s do yoga instead lol! 
@@@@@@@

text: 내 삶에는 많은 선택이 있었다. 그때마다 나는 나에게 이렇게 물었다. "지금 이 순간 더 어려운 선택은 무엇이고, 더 쉬운 선택은 무엇인가?" 답은 이미 정해져있었다. 나는 망설임 없이 더 어려운 선택을 선택했다. 어려운 선택을 하는 순간 오래된 낡은 패턴에 젖어있던 뇌가 깨어나면서 새로운 해결책을 찾아내는 일에 뛰어들기 때문이다. 이 새로운 해결책을 찾아내는 일에 뛰어드는 느낌, 이것이 곧 내가 살아야 할 가장 확실한 이유였다.

text:
@richardafowler

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
sure. ok. whatever you say.
looks like what he had called a “big victory” — was actually the long-anticiptaed #bluewave after all... it happened. it was the democratic party’s best midterm performance since 1974 – the year republican president richard nixon resigned over watergate. if he’s bothered by a little #rain... he can’t be liking this!
along with control of the house came pick-ups of 7+ governorships and scores of crucial statehouse seats nationwide. and the gop’s senate margin is going to be smaller than what trump had trumpeted. and as final results continue to come in, #democrats keep on winning. stop! please! democrats… i’m getting tired of so much winning!...
the work of the people has been on hold for two long years because the current house has been working for only one person… #illegitimate #failingpresident #donaldtrump.
mark your calendars… come january 3, the forwarding of legislation that the american people deserve and need — will resume. bill after bill will pass in the house… and be sent on to the senate — where, sure, senators can vote them all down — but at their own peril. those running for re-election to the upper chamber will need to explain to 2020 voters why they voted against so may popular and sensible reforms.
also resuming — long overdue oversight... corruption. ethics. russia. kavanaugh. tax returns. …you name it… now we can really start getting to the bottom of it. 
on election day we took the first big step to save #america… now we must end the #republican protection and enabling of the unindicted co-conspirator in the oval office: investigate… #trump #russia #washingtondc #lovetrumpshate #dumptrump #nevertrump #msnbc #cnn #foxnews #moveon #trumpprotest #notmypresident #politics #journalism #indivisible #makeamericagreatagain #maga #plannedparenthood #womensmarch #crazytown #metoo #resist

text:
.
.
🎞 アカデミー 栄光と悲劇
( 原題 introducing dorothy dandridge )
👤 主演 halle berry
.
ドロシー・ダンドリッジという
黒人女性(african american)のドキュメンタリー 。
.
当時の黒人隔離差別がわかる作品 。
表舞台ではキラキラに輝くドロシーも
ステージから下りれば blackというだけで差別の対象 。
この映画で衝撃的だったシーンが
白人専用トイレを使用できないこと 。
少し足をつけただけで水をを入れ替えられたこと。
あともう１つ気になったシーンは
白人から黒人に向ける差別に関してではないけど
黒人社会における女性の立場、地位の低さ 。
女性の言うことは通用しないという厳しい世界 。
これに気がついた時に思い出すのが #metoo #timesup 
改めていろんな問題について考えさせられました 。
映画の感想ですら うまく言葉に出来ないのは
自分の意見がまとまってないことなので
まだまだだなって改めて思いました 。
.
黒人女性初のアカデミー賞にノミネートされた
ドロシーのミュージカル映画『カルメン』も
これを演じたハリー・ベリーが
黒人女性初のアカデミー賞獲得した映画
『チョコレート』も観たいな観なきゃいけないな〜
.
ドロシーがlifeの表紙を飾ったあとに
尊意を示してハリーが同じようにlifeの表紙を飾った
という話を聞いて 
まさに“受け継がれる” “語り継がれる” だなあと
.
#アカデミー栄光と悲劇
#dorothydandridge #halleberry  #introducingdorothydandridge
.

text:
so feeling this! -
yes, the patriarchy is bad for men too: men suffer within it especially regarding the expectation to suppress their emotions and display toxic masculinity. -
however in so many areas of life, women pander to men: we endure, compromise and make ourselves small for male ego and comfort. -

i refuse to do that within feminism.
i am here for women.
-
not explain to men why they should feel empathy or spoon feed them topics they could google. -
i am here to tell of my experiences as a woman and elevate women's stories.
-
i am here to support and empower all the brilliant, tired, badass women out there who have been grinded down by this system we call the patriarchy. ✊🏻
-
-
-

text:
if you browse yoga studio timetables rarely do we see options such as women's yoga or men's yoga listed. in the age of equality do we need gender specific classes?

yes, yoga offers freedom to everyone, regardless of age, gender, ethnicity, or religion; but there are times when it can be more effective to teach to men or women only.

womens-only classes and environments are riding the current wave of female empowerment, women’s marches, and #metoo offer women of all shapes and abilities a supportive, ego-free environment enabling women to practice uninhibited.

there is definitely a need for a place in our busy lives and competitive society to come back to the beauty of being a woman. more and more women i speak to are hungry for a safe and sacred space to face their personal challenges, to get back in touch with their bodies without worrying about the ever growing to do list, to reconnect with other women who are all facing the same daily juggle of being a woman. a space to say fuck it for an hour, i need this time for me.
having 'sisters' is so ancient, and yet deeply needed in this present time. 
it should go without saying that being pro women doesn't make you anti men. and to be fair, not all women are welcoming and nonjudgmental. 
but there is something innately special knowing you are among like-minded sisters in a positive—and crap-free—atmosphere. 
womens yoga starting tonight @ 7pm

text:
sometimes silence is best...
many of us have used the phrase "if that were my kid, i would (insert words of choice)". as parents of a child sex abuse survivor, we had to eat those words as did many other parents of survivors. not to mention, we had to endure hearing them from others when they heard or read about a child being sexually abused. but, the truth of the matter is, you have no idea what you will do when faced with the reality that your child has been sexually abused. because, while your immediate inclination may be to tear the person who hurt them to shreds, all of your emotions have to be focused on making sure your child is taken care of and you are around to care for them in every way necessary moving forward. don't let other people's words; people who haven't experienced what your family is dealing with, make you feel like you failed as a parent if you didn't hurt or kill the person who harmed your child. at the end of the day, it's easy to say what you will do about a given situation until you're faced with it and your actions will have real consequences that might take you away from your child at a time when they really need you.  #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #sexcrimes #rapevictims #rape #victims #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate

text:
witches.
bitches.
whores.
liars.
we are literally rising up from the ashes of persecution, condemnation, torture, and murderous vendettas against our gender and/or spiritual gifts. 
i think it’s time to start talking about the witch wound in a way that honors all women. 
this is the frequency of an ancient, collective pain that has been preventing women from stepping fully into their power for centuries. 
a woman was considered a witch if she knew how to heal herself & others, spoke up for herself & other women or had sex out of wedlock, including rape. 
i avoided the highest expression of my path for as long as i could because the memories of being burned & butchered were still very much alive within me. 
i would spin in circles of self-doubt, frustration & anxiety —afraid to rise & afraid to hide. 
in a recent session, a client shared with me that some of her resistance around owning her purpose had to do with judgments against her by other women who publicly shame the trend of modern witchery, claiming that “coming out” as a witch or a shaman now that it’s “trendy” is a joke. 
i found this information deeply disturbing, because anyone who has authentically had to confront this word & this path, would not be capable of casting this level of darkness in the direction of another sister who is trying to find her way back. 
there are always exceptions. 
some people truly are dangerously dishonest about who they are, but that is not what we are addressing here. 
the unawakened woman is causing just as much pain & torment in the collective as the toxic masculine frequency. 
it’s now trendy to be a yogi, a shaman & a witch—obsessed with crystals, oils, astrology, and cats. 
thank the goddess!!!!
this is exactly what we have been preparing for. 
we are all at different stages of our feminine journey regardless of how we appear publicly or what we claim. 
flip you tarot cards, burn your sage, re-claim your power, start your business, show off your crystals, and flaunt your magic. 
your voice is sacred.
your body is sacred.
your story is sacred. 
and no one gets to decide who and what you are or aren’t anymore, but you! (cont’d 👇)
name: Goddess Medicine
tweet_full:
witches.
bitches.
whores.
liars.
we are literally rising up from the ashes of persecution, condemnation, torture, and murderous vendettas against our gender and/or spiritual gifts. 
i think it’s time to start talking about the witch wound in a way that honors all women. 
this is the frequency of an ancient, collective pain that has been preventing women from stepping fully into their power for centuries. 
a woman was considered a witch if she knew how to heal herself & others, spoke up for herself & other women or had sex out of wedlock, including rape. 
i avoided the highest expression of my path for as long as i could because the memories of being burned & butchered were still very much alive within me. 
i would spin in circles of self-doubt, frustration & anxiety —afraid to rise & afraid to hide. 
in a recent session, a client shared with me that some of her resistance around owning her purpose had to do with judgments against her by other women who publicly shame the trend of modern witchery, claiming that “coming out” as a witch or a shaman now that it’s “trendy” is a joke. 
i found this information deeply disturbing, because anyone who has authentically had to confront this word & this path, would not be capable of casting this level of darkness in the direction of another sister who is trying to find her way back. 
there are always exceptions. 
some people truly are dangerously dishonest about who they are, but that is not what we are addressing here. 
the unawakened woman is causing just as much pain & torment in the collective as the toxic masculine frequency. 
it’s now trendy to be a yogi, a shaman & a witch—obsessed with crystals, oils, astrology, and cats.

text:
“i believe that when we are trapped by our inability to evolve, by our inability to empathize humbly and painfully with others, that’s when we remain victims ourselves.” - monica lewinsky.
.
i haven’t heard a more truer line. (read the entire interview, link in bio)
.
we are unable to truly empathize with others because of the bitterness we hold on to, our conditioning, because we haven’t been empathized with we victimize others and we remain victims ourselves. it’s a vicious cycle. isn’t this the reason behind the disbelief of #metoo?
.
when bill clinton was asked why he engaged in an inappropriate relationship with monica lewinsky, he simply said, because he could! well now, it’s our time to tell our own stories in our own words, because we can! it took 20 years for the lewinsky scandal to become the clinton affair. it’s not too late. women are finally telling their stories and the world is splitting open, it’s happening.
.
the clinton affair premiers on 18th november on a&e. friends and family in us tune in. it’s a story about women told by women.

text: a medusa. possibly once a fertility symbol, she is in myth the more familiarly raging, man-destroying monster with roiling tresses, a gaze that turns onlookers to stone, and devastating teeth. once she was beautiful (the story goes) but raped by poseidon, she was punished by the avenging athena for her (!) crime. she was decapitated by perseus. here, the tresses are energetic tendrils and tender shoots. there are no venomous serpents or fearsome fangs. much to be said about medusa in #metoo times! a fascinating exhibition on currently: a dangerous woman: medusa in classical art at metropolitan museum of art, ny. see also mary beard, woman and power (2018) and helene cixous ‘the laugh of the medusa’ (1976)(!) #mythsand monsters #tentacularthinking #medusainart #dangerouswoman #cutpaper

signs in the rearview mirror: leaving a toxic relationship behind by kelly smith @kellysmithauthor 
what kind of person ends up in a toxic relationship? and why does she stay? this searingly honest novel answers both those questions head-on. coming out of a failing marriage, kelly turns to gabe out of fear of being alone. her gradual slide into danger is at once terrifying and inevitable, and the steps she takes to get out of it will both inspire and offer hope.

text:
@richardafowler @richardojedawv

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
these past few weeks have been hectic, to say the least. i was traveling the week of halloween, the week after that i got a dog (a first for me!), midterm elections were emotionally exhausting, this week i hosted family members visiting from out of town, my day job has been busy, i’ve been looking for a new therapist, i’ve been trying to work out every day… it’s been a lot. throw daily maintenance and engagement of a brand new social media presence on the pile, and woah buddy. i needed a break. i didn’t plan it. i didn’t announce it. i just took it because that’s what needed to happen for me. •

when my routine is interrupted by anything- be it positive or negative- i become… discomfited. i’m easily overwhelmed, irritable, distracted. the smallest setback can set off a tidal wave of negative self talk or, worse yet, a panic attack. my natural response to this scenario is to shut down. in the same way that the body sacrifices extremities to survive frostbite, i preserve what little energy i have and send it inward, killing off the appendages of unnecessary interaction, social media engagement, and interpersonal relationships because i can’t spare the fuel. i don’t do it to be callous or cruel, i do it to make myself feel protected until i can find safety in my routine again. survivorship is what we do to stay alive. we know it’s not glamorous. we know it’s not always the healthiest route. (and we’re working on that.) but we’re still here. alive. i may not post on a schedule. i may not respond to every comment or add to my story every hour. or every day. or even every week. but that doesn’t mean i’m gone. until further notice, i’m still here, using what energy i can spare to keep myself- and all survivors- warm. ✨ #copingmechanisms #selfcare #survival #anxiety #cptsd #mentalhealthawareness #survivor #survivorselfcare #metoo #artist #workinprogress

text:

•
on the other hand, the mood & pace of instagram is different 😉@mother_of_daughters has just posted about this and has really made me think. •
•
•
which social media platform do you prefer and why?

text:
i came across this in my iphone notepad today...some-thing i wrote in may this year (2018) ...just after the ‘official split’ but just over a month before i moved out of the marital home. not a poem or a song...just my feelings....and coming across these words 6months after the fact, makes me feel rather proud of myself because the path i have traveled over the last 6mths have been in line with these very words! this is a rear-view look at my current journey, and a starting point to my thought processes before my journey even began! #wordsintoactions #actionsspeaklouderthanwords 
thoughts of the day💭
finding my voice and a sense of who i am has changed every single aspect of my life! it has changed me, challenged me & channeled me - physically, mentally, emotionally and spiritually! 
over the last 6months, i have allowed myself to be spiritually led - even though my heart bled - and i’m not gonna lie....it’s been rough ride! i am not the same person who wrote these words 6mths ago...but at the same time, i am still that person....does that even make sense? whatever the case, i have learnt to love who i was, who i am and who i am yet to become...and i can’t wait to see where the next 6mths takes me!❤️ #tyj #thoughts #feelings #words #actions #cptsd #survivor #thriver #understandingourtrauma #roadtorecovery #healingjourney #faithbasedsupport #whereleavingisnotthefirstoption #abuseisnotlove #selfworth #selfrespect #selflove #selfloveisnotselfish 💖 #livingwithapurpose #writingforacause #sharingourstory #raisingawareness #domesticviolenceadvocate #metoo #itaintweaktospeak

text:
the biggest lie that rattled around my head for 20+ years was that i was not worth anything. *worthless*
this whisper became a scream at certain times.
sometimes i believed it so strongly that i slumped back and didnt accomplish all that i know i could have. 
what is the truth? 
my name, my given birth name means the exact opposite. 
what does your name mean? dont accept anything less. 
#iampriceless #sexualabuse
#metoo #nolongeraslave #shepersisted #wheniwas

text:
now in my late 40s there’s a shift in me. i’m still as impulsive and reactive as i was when i was 18, but now i have a structure and language to my fury. at 18 i never understood what i was furious at. it’s taken 30 years of asking questions, wearing my heart on my sleeve, falling flat on my face and floods of tears to build a language to communicate that frustration and anger. the language didn’t just come together overnight. it’s taken years of diligence and consistent effort. ultimately, steel snd thread became the words and the craft became the grammar. materiality and craft gave birth to how i wanted us to think of ourselves...... as females and males. i got to tap into ideas bigger than us. i got to tap into the internal dialogue. .
so what is it? ....that internal torment..... and why is it that till today  i find myself battling with the same questions? ‘why have women allowed men to do the thinking for them?’
think about every smile you’ve faked and every roast you’ve baked...... can we act out of free will? 
are we just products of our circumstances and inherited psychosis of our ancestors? •asl  notebooks, 2018, female psyche studies. 
@asleninde

text:
now in my late 40s there’s a shift in me. i’m still as impulsive and reactive as i was when i was 18, but now i have a structure and language to my fury. at 18 i never understood what i was furious at. it’s taken 30 years of asking questions, wearing my heart on my sleeve, falling flat on my face and floods of tears to build a language to communicate that frustration and anger. the language didn’t just come together overnight. it’s taken years of diligence and consistent effort. ultimately, steel snd thread became the words and the craft became the grammar. materiality and craft gave birth to how i wanted us to think of ourselves...... as females and males. i got to tap into ideas bigger than us. i got to tap into the internal dialogue. -
so what is it? ..... that internal torment..... and why is it that till today  i find myself battling with the same questions? ‘why have women allowed men to do the thinking for them?’
think about every smile you’ve faked and every roast you’ve baked...... can we act out of free will? 
are we just products of our circumstances and inherited psychosis of our ancestors? •asl  notebooks, 2018, female psyche studies.

text:
now in my late 40s there’s a shift in me. i’m still as impulsive and reactive as i was when i was 18, but now i have a structure and language to my fury. at 18 i never understood what i was furious at. it’s taken 30 years of asking questions, wearing my heart on my sleeve, falling flat on my face and floods of tears to build a language to communicate that frustration and anger. the language didn’t just come together overnight. it’s taken years of diligence and consistent effort. ultimately, steel snd thread became the words and the craft became the grammar. materiality and craft gave birth to how i wanted us to think of ourselves...... as females and males. i got to tap into ideas bigger than us. i got to tap into the internal dialogue. -
so what is it? ..... that internal torment..... and why is it that till today  i find myself battling with the same questions? ‘why have women allowed men to do the thinking for them?’
think about every smile you’ve faked and every roast you’ve baked...... can we act out of free will? 
are we just products of our circumstances and inherited psychosis of our ancestors? •asl  notebooks, 2018, female psyche studies.

text: la soledad de la feminidad. no hay nada más solitario que estar bajo la mirada de todo el mundo. este dibujo es inspirado en la película "les femmes du bus" y expresa el sentimiento de las mujeres cuando sufren de acosos o abusos y además de todo les echan la culpa, las señalan, las miran y aprovechan para sexualizarlas aún más. también pasa cuando abortan, cuando trabajan, o cuando hacen cualquier acto libre con el que la sociedad no esté de acuerdo. y para colmo todo el mundo les da la espalda y las insulta. viva el sistema!

text:
mi., 14.11..2018, ab 16:00 uhr für 3-5 € im wohnzimmer: plattentresen mit  sigourney skywalker & maidengawd - ab 19:30 hinter den alpen: form vs. prezident - streitgespräch
☛
plattentresen mit sigourney und maidengawd - beide schmeissen musikalische sonderbares im besten sinne aufs parkett und umschmeicheln eure trommelfelle mit einer entspannten wohnzimmer-session. ein plattentresen, zum träumen schön am tresen und zum tanzen gut auf den dielen.
☛
form/ prim vs. prezident/ whiskeyrap - ein streitgespräch, das euch vom splash! mag präsentiert wird. - form und prezident sind zwei antipoden im rap-game. form, seines zeichens selbsternannter gutmensch, aktivist und rapper geht an die wunden punkte der deutschsprachigen rapszene und wendet sich gegen sexismus, rassismus und antisemititsmus. der wuppertaler prezident hat mit äußerungen im rahmen seiner letzten platte “du hast mich schon verstanden” echte kontroversen geschaffen: die #metoo-bewegung bezeichnete der selbst ernannte nihilist und zyniker in einem interview als “kollektivpsychose”, den angeblich “linken, moralischen rigorismus” zieht prezident regelmäßig durch den kakao. nach der medialen aufregung im sommer, nehmen sich prezident und form zeit die kontroverse auf der bühne auszutragen.
☛

form/ prim vs. prezident/ whiskeyrap - ein streitgespräch, das euch vom splash! mag präsentiert wird. - form und prezident sind zwei antipoden im rap-game. form, seines zeichens selbsternter gutmensch, aktivist und rapper geht an die wunden punkte der deutschsprachigen rapszene und wendet sich gegen sexismus, rassismus und antisemititsmus. der wuppertaler prezident hat mit äußerungen im rahmen seiner letzten platte “du hast mich schon verstanden” echte kontroversen geschaffen: die #metoo-bewegung bezeichnete der selbst ernte nihilist und zyniker in einem interview als “kollektivpsychose”, den angeblich “linken, moralischen rigorismus” zieht prezident regelmäßig durch den kakao. nach der medialen aufregung im sommer, nehmen sich prezident und form zeit die kontroverse auf der bühne auszutragen.
☛

'tied up' is a statement about humanity, our diversity and many ranges of our emotions. 
one of the qualities that make us sentient is the society we have built and the web of relationships we are a part of. we try to find balance in ourselves and in our relationships. 
moments of bliss, clarity and togetherness punctuated by moments of struggle and confusion, we are all essentially tied up together.

text:
ptsd and anxiety. an awful combination. it's not about being anxious about what can happen, it's about being anxious about what already happened in the past.
i often feel anxious in crowded public places. when you don't have enough personal space and everyone touches you (by accident). i am happy to live in a small village with a population of 2000 people and not in a big city. 
when i'm with friends or family i always try to hide my anxiety attacks. 
my heart beats like crazy, i feel hot but my hands are cold and i begin to freeze. my mouth is dry and i get tunnel vision. my brain doesn't work right and i don't know what to say or i'm stuttering. and i'm afraid. i'm really afraid.
i hate it. because there's nothing you can really do about it except learning to live with it.
.
.

text:
i don’t usually do long posts but here goes…
spirit said, “as long as you care about what others think of you, you will never be as great as you could be.” today is a big day for me. i will stand in my truth and testify against sean arthur (vahrly), who violated my consent by recording our sexual encounters without my knowledge. it took a lot for me to write that. *exhale* for the past ten months i have struggled with shame, anger, fear, sadness, and anxiety as i tried to wrap my head around this.

now i understand why victims of sexual violence do not come forward. what if no one believes me? what if he hurts me? what will people think? all of this ran through my mind. despite the emotional toll, i kept going, especially since he had other victims. growing up, people would ask me to be the one to speak up and i wondered “why me?” i realize that those moments prepared me for this one. my voice may quiver, tears will probably fall, and i’ll likely want to vomit. i’m scared. i still won’t be silenced.

let's all do our part in demolishing rape culture and changing the collective consciousness around consent. recording sexual encounters without consent is a felony. removing condoms without consent is rape. pressuring your partner is abuse. only yes means yes. and yes, consent is required each and every single time. beforehand. most of the women i know have experienced some level of sexual abuse. it is not enough for us to talk among each other. men, you get to support us by having conversations about consent with other men, women, and young people in your lives. 
the picture above was taken in may when a community of amazing souls reminded me of the queen i am. and they had no idea what i was going through. nothing will ever mar my divinity within. my light will never dim.
.
.
#domesticviolence #metoo #consent #endrapeculture #onlyyesmeansyes #believewomen #socialjustice #ibelieveher #sexualabuse #nomeansno #selflove #dvam #speakyourtruth #vulnerability #survivor #justice #testify #love #ripoldme #ibelievesurvivors #silencebreaker #misogyny #blackwomenmatter #throatchakra #shiva #reportabusers #sociopaths #narcissists #binded

napkins were distributed to the underprivileged women and girls. health awareness was spread and sanitary napkin usage was taught.

please help us. we need your support.

please donate on paytm @ 8104107086

visit us @ www.jeevanarth.org

text:
this is where it all started. even as a kid i was extremely sensitive to the surroundings. thinking of it as a weakness i grew up with a lot resentment, anger, bitterness and sadness. for the major part of life it has been the same . making merry with that child has always been a struggle. now when i look back, when things have changed drastically, when i’ve had a chance to lose myself and then finding back multiple times, i realise those were actually some of the most beautiful and cherishable moments ever
.
we all grow up with certain struggles . some physical , some emotional , some mental. i grew up with a mix of them . the first change started at the physical level that’s why i do what i do today. the emotional and mental ones, well they are toughest ones and the journey to master them will continue for a long time ahead. but atleast i understand the fact that being sensitive is actually a strength rather than a weakness. it does call for more resilience and can be draining at times, but if channelised in the right direction, could turn out to be a superpower
.
a huge shoutout to my childhood friend @tarun_veer_goyal for all the good and the bad times we’ve been together
.
#goodtimes #thegrindisthelife #childhoodmemories #schoolmemories #nostalgia #patiala #memory #superkid

text:
@richardafowler - bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
@richardafowler - bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr

text:
"hr professionals are asking how should one deal with complaints by employees on social media if an official report has not been filed. #metoo is a reaction to the dire conditions of our times, but this cannot be the new norm. when internal processes are robust and victims feel confident that justice will be served without personal persecution, then they will feel no need to turn to social media.

how many employees know about their rights when it comes to workplace harassment? how many hr teams really function beyond the shadows of the company promoters and owners? the real shift needs to happen there. hr community needs to be empowered as well as sensitised to create systems that work irrespective of designation of the accused." read the full article: link in bio.

text:
dear world,

i tried to try my best but unfortunately this is the best i have. despite being a tiny quarter pounder i am also just a tiny lonesome human being.

now, you can use the information and the shitload of shit produced in the shithole country of mine as you will. however, please note that i might have commited some copyright violations.

do not do as i say or do as i do - consider carefully what is the right and responsible action and then just do it and keep doing it until.

as far as i know hillary might as well be a criminal but i'm pretty sure that obama is not the antichrist, jesus is not coming back and building any temples or golden ivory towers of babel or blasphemous church militants will not make any positive miracles happen.

instead of fighting over hypocritical opinions, sunken dreams and perverse fantasies we should take care of each other and this planet.

politicians are just people with commitments too and corporations will never risk their profits trying to find any truly sustainable solutions. if we want to save our children or even dream making something great again unfortunately we all need to take the responsibility, right here, right now.

the solution will not be found left or right - you and only you can be the solution.

this is not a game, this is the war. let's not make it any worse, ok?

unite, take care and be safe. all the best from finland! 💪😘👍 .

text:
let’s face it. 
i am a victim.
sexual abuse in your own home, in your apparent “safe space”, during your most vulnerable years.
there were times i thought i’m going crazy, and there were times i thought i knew it all. 
now i know: escaping is good, confrontation is better.
all i need is love. peace with my family - my dear mother, my dear sister. keep the faith.
i’m begging for forgiveness if i broke anyone’s heart or treated anyone in an inappropriate way. i ask for understanding that i also had to fight to survive. 
thank you eddie, my dude, for encouraging me to speak up for myself and being the great person that you are to help me gain back some strength and trust in men. love you lots my dude, can’t wait for you and sach to come visit ♥️
#metoo #metwo #pedophelia #makethepersonalpolitical

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
@richardafowler

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
@richardafowler

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
as i walk through this season of finding my voice and helping others find theirs, i am told i am brave. 
what does it mean to be brave?

1. be willing to stand up for injustice. 
2. be willing to step out of your comfort zones.  3. brave not because  you're not scared but but because you do it anyway.
4. brave by stepping into your own story and being being vulnerable.
5. being a warrior.  the woman who dares to break the chains of oppression off her life. to shatter every prison that has held her bound. to soar into her purpose. 
6. brave by forgiving her abuser. it takes bravery to begin restoration. and become whole. and admit i was not fine.  to not pretend i was fine.  not seeing it as a threat but as an invitation from the holy spirit.
7. being brave is not hiding from the pain
8. being brave is standing up and saying,  no decision by anyone is going to define me, that i'm a beloved child of god.
circumstances can't define me. i will stand with my head held high with girlfriends around me holding up my arms when i can't lift them anymore  #lovewins #hopegiver #kingdombuilders #breakthesilence #speakyourtruth #jesussaves #brave #bravewomen #mommyhood #lifeischoice

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

that’s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him “we can take it.” no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but it’s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then it’s easy to come along for the ride. there’s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they’re both just characters on the television.

that’s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. it’s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. it’s that we’ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

that’s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him “we can take it.” no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but it’s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then it’s easy to come along for the ride. there’s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they’re both just characters on the television.

that’s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. it’s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. it’s that we’ve lost the capacity to treat civics, goverce, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text:
i’ve taken self love, reiki and holistic wellness to a whole ‘nother level! i recently hosted my first retreat with nine women. we set intentions, we supported each other, we ate healthy meals, we cried, laughed, hiked, hugged, had sound healing, group reiki, massage, guided meditation, qigong, oracle card readings and most importantly this was a safe space i created for us to be our most authentic selves and to really take the time to hear our thoughts and feel our feels.

it was a retreat that i wanted each woman to feel empowered with new perspectives and tools when she left the retreat and integrated into her daily life.

most women had breakthroughs. every woman learned something new about themselves. i am so grateful for the experience and i’m already planning the next one.

text:
i recently learned a new term. “the absence of presence.” in art the term is expressed to describe the ways that we are remembered even when we aren’t present. for example, a stained wine glass left on the table after dinner, or for me, a trail of shoes, jewelry, and bags scattered around the house after a day of meetings. while i might not be present, those items are reminders that i exist, even in my absence. 🌱
.
.
.
and i’ve been thinking a lot about this concept in terms of my soul. and the marks (both good and bad) that we leave on a person. there is a presence that people have indelibly etched into me that have shaped who i am. and even though they are now absent in my life, their presence is felt for better or for worse. 🌱
.
.
.
the question i’ve been pondering is this: do i leave people with a mark on their soul that is a positive presence long after our interaction, or do i leave people with a negative one? and what difference might that make? 🌱
.
.
.
cs lewis says, “there are no ordinary people. you have never talked to a mere mortal. nations, cultures, arts, civilizations - these are mortal, and their life is to ours as the life of a gnat. but it is immortals whom we joke with, work with, marry, snub, and exploit - immortal horrors or everlasting splendors.” 🌱
.
.
.
i mess up so much. but in my heart of hearts, long after my presence, i long to have left a redeeming mark on a person. may my presence fill people with hope and wonder. that is my prayer. 🌱

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

⚠️ самые опасные страны для женщин: где страшнее жить и отдыхать⚠️часть 1⚠️
▫️казалось бы, в современном цивилизованном обществе женщины давно отстояли равные с мужчинами права, в том числе и право на безопасность. но планету по-прежнему сотрясают феминистические протесты, цели которых не слишком поменялись за последние сотни лет. в их географии — развивающаяся азия, с трудом выбирающаяся из нищеты африка и даже внешне благополучные европа и сша. но есть страны, где женщинам по-настоящему опасно не только жить, но и отдыхать, и их перечень явно стоит изучить при планировании следующего отпуска.
⚫️индия — лидер печального списка
▪️фонд the thomson reuters недавно составил рейтинг самых недружелюбных к женщинам стран. в исследовании участвовали 550 экспертов, оценивавших ситуацию с насилием и дискриминацией во всем мире. непочетное 1-е место заняла индия, где крайне высоки риски сексуального насилия и рабского труда. еще несколько лет назад она была 4-й, но упорно продолжает пренебрегать женскими правами: изнасилования, преследования, нападения, детские браки, калечащие операции мало кого удивляют и редко влекут должное наказание.
▪️ежегодно в индии совершаются 12 млн абортов; доступ к образованию есть лишь у 10 % женщин; почти половина из 3 млн индийских проституток несовершеннолетние; за минувшее столетие пропали без вести около 50 млн девушек.
⚫️ кто наступает индии на пятки
▪️следующий в списке — афганистан, место и в целом далекое от идиллии. по данным юнисеф, 80 % афганских девочек отдают замуж несовершеннолетними, одна из 11 рожениц умирает, 91 % женщин сталкиваются с физическим и сексуальным насилием, 87 % неграмотны. после краха режима талибов заметен определенный прогресс, но динамика все еще неутешительна.
▪️ главная боль конго — сексуальное насилие, коему каждый час подвергаются 48 женщин (в сутки получается 1152). в сомали царит беззаконие: на образование могут рассчитывать около 1 % женщин, 86 % недоедают, каждая 14-я умирает при родах, в нормальных условиях вообще рожают лишь 9 %.
👇продолжение👇

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

zafigox is a safe space for women to come together and inspire each other. to share the joys and the challenges of going for one's dream. to create strong networks and make new friendships. 🙌
biggest thanks to marina, james, maggie, eliza and the rest of the @zafigoasia team for creating such an incredible event and allowing me to be part of it. i look forward to more zafigox.
.

text:
#swipeleft yesterday, we visited two schools; a primary school and a secondary school. one of the things we do on this tour is give each girl a piece of paper as we talk to them, where they can write their questions or tell us if they are being sexually abused. when we get to do a screening of these papers after collecting them, we are stunned by what we see. it’s alarming the number of girls and the ages, in fact.
.
.
this, indeed, is a rescue mission. from number of girls we have realized so far, we’ve decided to dedicate more time than we had planned, towards helping these girls heal, as that’s our overall aim. for this reason, we are cutting down on the number of schools we will visit this month, and a number of other decisions which we will communicate soon.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
i've been documenting protests on-and-off for ten years now and i feel the tide turning in a beautiful way: i am seeing activists are freely speaking and leading from the heart in a way that i have never seen before
*
#metoo has brought a powerful vulnerability that has been wrongly shamed and cast as victimhood: all along it has been about the emotional truths of survivors
*
it has been a way for all survivors to connect with one another stripping down the bullshit, shame, agendas and power structures that have prevented those who were once marginalized from getting deep & real
*
saturday was more than a march or protest, it was a gathering of a more inclusive movement, the missing pieces of occupy with many  groups represented- including latin american indigenous women leading the way. the intersection of poc survivors, cis women and men survivors, lgbtq+ survivors, homeless survivors, disabled survivors followed
*
we listened to the stories of gay and trans survivors, heard about the rising movement in india, among others
*
the speakers before and after showed a beautiful rawness that you won't ever see on the mainstream news
*
these are just some of the people driving change. we have them to thank for taking the chance to raise their voices in public spaces, here in a crowded tourist area no less, in hopes future generations never have to say #metoo again
*
a new day is truly on the horizon ❤

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
entertainment | #metoo : cintaa expels alok nath

details: bollywood actor alok nath, who is alleged to have sexually harassed writer-producer vinta nanda 19 years ago, was on tuesday expelled by the cine and television artistes association (cintaa). the association wrote on twitter, “in view of the various allegations of sexual harassment and misconduct against alok nath, after due diligence and consideration, the executive committee of cintaa has decided to expel him from the association.” as the #metoo movement gained momentum, with women coming out with their horror stories vis-a-vis sexual harassment at workplace, nanda shared her account of harassment by alok nath who was acting in the television show ‘tara’ in which she was a producer and writer.

after sharing her experience of harassment on social media, she filed a case against alok nath at the oshiwara police station.

#metoo #indianews #vintananda #aloknath #bollywood #pratidintime

text:
house of cards... recently, season 6 of "house of cards" was streamed on netflix (8 episodes). having watched the earlier 5 seasons very ardently, this should have been a binge watching... but... the plot got too complicated, too many back stories, which one couldn't remember. and of course, kevin spacey as frank underwood is conveniently murdered, as an after effect of #metoo!

robin wright as clair underwood, the current president, is still wonderful and mysterious, and so is doug.. the ultimate "chamcha ", who goes on to become an afterlife chamcha, intent on destroying claire

but the plot drags, and one is almost thankful for the end!

for me season 6 is 2/5, but still a must watch for fans of " house of cards "

text:
never let a bad situation bring out the worst in you. be strong and chose to be positive 🌸🙏🏼
—————————————————————
over the past 2.5 years i have been subjected to sexual and verbal harassment from an individual on a reoccurring basis. a couple of nights ago this person took it too far making me feel un safe in a place that i hold near and dear to my heart, a place that i should feel the most safe. it was in this moment that i decided i am done being quiet. i am done standing by and watching the bullying and abuse this person subjects to not just women but people he has created power dominant relationships with. it has taken me years to feel comfortable and confident in these spaces and i just feel like i am being pushed back into a place of distrust and honestly am struggling even going. but i know that this is the time i need to reach out, dig deep and keep my head up because i am not going to let this person take my power that i have spent years tapping into. i definitely wouldn’t feel comfortable speaking up if it weren’t for my friends who witnessed this past weeks event and for all of the people who made me feel supported and safe. as much as i love my #girlgang and am riding that girl power wave hard these days, i am also grateful for the men who have rallied around me so i can feel safe late at night when i need a place to share and listen. ——————————————————————

text:
coach stephie juice alarms•
•
4:45am: you are energy ❤️
6:00am: today i’m going to believe that showing up is enough
9:00am: you. are. enough. 
2:00pm: faith over fear; be still
3:51pm: what are you grateful for today?
7:00pm: share some love with someone.•
•
every single day these alarms go off no matter where i am and yet every single time they do go off, it’s exactly what i need to hear. 
every afternoon at 3:51pm i say (sometimes out loud) what i’m immediately grateful for. and if i hit snooze by accident instead of reset... i say more things when it goes off again.•
•
this has been suggested to me multiple times over the years and i’m telling you i wish i had done it sooner. these strong messages of grace and gratitude are sometimes what get me through a really tough moment, and always keeps my mind coming back to love and surrender.•
•
i will do all the easy things to keep me focused on growth and forward movement. i am telling you this is easy. •
•
if you end up doing this please share with me your successes and outcomes. truly, it won’t ever ruin your day to think of your future self and offer her all the kindness in the world. 🌎

text:
congresswoman not seeking re-election after mishandling harassment issue (hartford, conn.) —u.s. rep. elizabeth esty announced monday she will not seek re-election this year amid calls for her resignation over her handling of the firing of a former chief of staff accused of harassment, threats and violence against female staffers in her congressional office.
 esty, a democrat from connecticut and an outspoken #metoo advocate, was accused of not protecting female staffers from the ex-chief of staff. esty has said she regrets not moving along an internal investigation into the allegations, which revealed more widespread allegations of abuse, and regrets providing “even the slightest assistance to this individual as he sought a new job.” esty said she determined “that it is in the best interest of my constituents and my family to end my time in congress at the end of this year and not seek re-election.” her announcement came hours after she asked the house ethics committee to review her actions. “although we worked with the house employment counsel to investigate and ultimately dismiss this employee for his outrageous behavior with a former staffer, i believe it is important for the house ethics committee to conduct its own inquiry into this matter,” esty said in a written statement, acknowledging “it certainly was far from a perfect process.” esty said she wants the committee to “clarify whether there was any wrongdoing” on her part.
 a lawyer for the committee said he could not comment on esty’s request for an investigation. it’s unclear whether an investigative subcommittee will be created or how long the process might take.
 the request for an expedited probe from esty came amid calls for her resignation from a growing number of state politicians in connecticut, including fellow democrats. bob duff, the democratic state senate’s majority leader, was among those to urge esty to step down in the midst of her third-term.
 duff said several points led him to call for esty’s resignation, including her reluctance to speak out publicly about the situation and using taxpayer money to pay her former chief of staff, tony baker, about $5,000 in severance.

text: unicycling for voting today. voting is one opportunity to challenge what are becoming norms in our country. the results of this past november 6th have demonstrated change is possible, but is slow. it is not okay to separate babies from their parents. it is not okay to ban visitors or put up walls based on racism. it is not okay that black americans live in fear of being killed by the police. it is not okay that the queer community has been stripped of the little protections and progresses made on that front. it is not okay that schools and places of worship have had the highest incidence of shootings than ever before in us history. it is not okay that the wealthiest in this country are getting enormous tax cuts, while the rest of us can barely afford housing and healthcare for ourselves and our families. it is not okay that supreme court justices and other men in power have not been held accountable for sexual assault. this is unacceptable. please vote! especially if you are in a district that has a different majority.

text:
we're so honored to be the beneficiary of this fabulous new compilation album by @dazzleships_records! "raised by women" features 11 of portland's most talented artists, all of whom have generously donated their tracks.
.
100% of vinyl sales and all $8 door sales at their release event on december 12th at @thefixinto will be donated to support our life-saving services for survivors of domestic violence.
.
join us next month to celebrate this phenomenal group of female artists! and in the meantime, preview their beautiful collection of music via the link in our bio.
.
we’ve been listening on repeat and can’t say thanks enough to #dazzleshiprecords and @skull_divuh, @miniblindz, @cathochmusic, @natashakmeto, @rillaban, @johahahanna, @dandansynth, @blackwaterholylight, @laurapalmersdeathparade, @hastetheband, and @lilysheers.
.

text:
"clarity: a storytelling event" is in 5 days, featuring susan burton 11/17 at 2pm at mercado la paloma @mercadolapaloma, conference room. 3655 s. grand avenue in la. free and open to the public. 
co-sponsored by a new way of life reentry project @anewwayoflifela and by the ralph j. bunche center for african-american studies at ucla @bunchecenter

more info: repairconnect.org/events 
about susan: susan burton’s story in overcoming overwhelming odds is an inspiration to people across the nation, particularly women formerly incarcerated or in recovery from addiction. after a personal tragedy, susan’s suffering resulted in a cycle inside the criminal justice system for nearly two decades. susan persevered, founding a new way of life re-entry project (anwol) in 1998. susan is a recognized leader in the criminal justice reform & re-entry rights movements. for her efforts, susan was named a cnn top ten hero in 2010 & awarded the prestigious citizen activist award from the harvard kennedy school of government. in 2013, anwol was honored with a ford freedom unsung award that salutes "organizations that have positively impacted communities with achievements that inform and inspire others.” susan is a recipient of both the encore purpose prize (2012) & james irvine foundation leadership award (2014). earlier this year the los angeles times named susan burton as one of the nation’s civil rights leaders of the 21st century. 
#susanburton #civilrights #picoftheday #losangeles #ucla #blackwomen #womenleaders #africanamericanleaders #formerlyincarcerated #reentry #criminaljusticereform #clarity #transformation #storytelling #healing #socialaction #socialchange #socialjustice #racialjustice #survivors #metoo #yesallwomen #freeevents #community #women #gender

text:
💜😀me and this big, wide kool-aid smile have come a long way. it's the feature that most people would compliment me on most of my life but for a long time i lost my smile. i would smile every now and again but it was typically one of those fake smiles that never reach the eyes. (sincere smiles light up the eyes.) i went through the motions faking happiness for the sake of my family, my marriage. 
known as a serial optimist for years before this, i had family members who would distance themself from me because i was too positive, too happy. oddly when my true smile began to fade, those people became way more comfortable with me but i began to feel as if i was someone else. some major things i went through caused me to start to doubt everything and everyone in my life and i didn't recognize myself. i didn't like the person i saw in the mirror. she was weak and tired. she had stopped dreaming, stopped believing in life's possibilities. she'd stopped believing in herself. i hated her. i felt worthless. i felt unloved, uncared for, unworthy of anything good in life. i felt like a failure, a waste. i felt unworthy of living. 
but god... i smile now because i know that he is working things out in my favor. i am more comfortable in my own skin. i am becoming a woman i can be proud of. i am in love with her. i am still in the process of recovering from so many great losses and setbacks in my life but i know there is greater ahead so i smile big. 😀

name: It's all for His glory 🙏🏾
tweet_full:
💜😀me and this big, wide kool-aid smile have come a long way. it is the feature that most people would compliment me on most of my life but for a long time i lost my smile. i would smile every now and again but it was typically one of those fake smiles that never reach the eyes. (sincere smiles light up the eyes.) i went through the motions faking happiness for the sake of my family, my marriage. 
known as a serial optimist for years before this, i had family members who would distance themself from me because i was too positive, too happy. oddly when my true smile began to fade, those people became way more comfortable with me but i began to feel as if i was someone else. some major things i went through caused me to start to doubt everything and everyone in my life and i didn't recognize myself. i didn't like the person i saw in the mirror. she was weak and tired. she had stopped dreaming, stopped believing in life's possibilities. she'd stopped believing in herself. i hated her. i felt worthless. i felt unloved, uncared for, unworthy of anything good in life. i felt like a failure, a waste. i felt unworthy of living. 
but god... i smile now because i know that he is working things out in my favor. i am more comfortable in my own skin. i am becoming a woman i can be proud of. i am in love with her. i am still in the process of recovering from so many great losses and setbacks in my life but i know there is greater ahead so i smile big. 😀 
#shesmiles ☺#sheslays 💁
#shegrinds 📝📑📈🎶 #sheprays 🙏
#love #blessed #smile #livingmybestlife #keepsmiling #keepgoing #shesaboss #selflove #sheisaqueen #sheissomethingserious #shesabeast #affirmations #selfesteem #lovingme #buildingmeup #ifnotmethenwho #speakingaboutmyselfinthethirdperson 
#soundinglike@tamarbraxton #tamarbraxton #metoo #mrw #beyondproverbs31

can we please take even a hot minute to celebrate this amazing woman's success!?
not only is she a mom, she is a successful photography  business owner. we all know photography is not a 40-hour a week position. it runs you ragged. and that on top of children, pto, sports and other extra curriculars.
.
yet, she still finds time for her. time to better herself, mentally, emotionally and physically. .
this is the kind of woman that i look up to. the kind of woman that is in my life, on my team and in my corner. we root for each other, we motivate and inspire each other.
.
an all-woman team of this caliber?? i thought this was the stuff of dreams. i thought women like these were unicorns.
.
it's not. they're not. we exist. and you can be part of this too.
.
